title: phantasy_star_iii
body:
[i][b]Phantasy Star III: Descendants of Time[/b][/i] (released in the west as [i][b]Phantasy Star III: Generations of Doom[/b][/i]) is the third [[video game]] in the [[Phantasy Star]] science fiction and [[fantasy]] RPG series for the [[Sega Mega Drive]]/Sega Genesis home console by [[SEGA]]. 

It was released in Japan during late 1990 and worldwide in 1991.

The player has the choice of selecting to marry one of two female characters from his companion party producing different offspring that become the next generation's hero, which continues for three in-game generations.

[spoiler]The game's plot takes place 1,000 years after the time period of [[Phantasy Star IV]] (2,000 years after [[Phantasy Star II]] and 3,000 years after [[Phantasy Star I]]).

It is set inside a massive colonization [[spacecraft]] divided in different sections (or "kingdoms") that contain the descendants of the last surviving refugees from planet Palm of the Algol System. 

This planet was destroyed during the events of the second game in the series.[/spoiler]

Dani Rojas is the protagonist of Far Cry 6. They are either male or female depending on the player's choice, but they can't be customized nor renamed. Unlike the previous two games, Dani is more heavily involved in the plot and is a fully-voiced protagonist.

It is probable that the female is the canonical protagonist because the game defaults to the female character when creating a new game.

Dani was born and raised in Yara's capital city. A military dropout, Dani did not want to join the Revolution and instead wished to escape the country. Dani eventually gets swept up in the Guerilla movement and now has the goal to take on Antón in the Lion's Den, a nickname for the capital of Yara. It is revealed in the first moments of the game that Dani was an orphan. They describe how in their childhood they rigged a bike with a chainsaw.

After the fall of Castilo regime, most resistance leaders appoint Dani as the next El Presidente but Dani does not feel like a person who can manage the country so Dani let the leaders of the resistance factions to decide but in Dani's mind, Dani does not have much faith in them.

title: dysfunctional_systems
body:
Visual novel by Dischan, currently on hiatus.

h4. Synopsis:

Dysfunctional Systems is an episodic visual novel chronicling the life of [[Winter Harrison]]. Having long become comfortable with her utopian society, Winter is surprised to learn that there are other worlds in other planes of existence. These worlds are quite different from hers, ranging from troubled, to dystopian, to futuristic or fantastical. However, they are all riddled with problems that, if not resolved, may adversely affect her home world. She is chosen to become a "mediator", charged with the maintenance of order in these chaotic planes, and so enters a vocational school for training. Episode 1 details her second shadowing of a seasoned mediator, only a few weeks into her first year. She and her mentor enter a world seemingly much like their own, except for this issue of "poverty" with which Winter has difficulty understanding...

title: guillotine
body:
A machine used to conduct [[execution]]s by [[decapitation]] originating in [[France]].

A typical guillotine consists of a large, heavy blade suspended between two tall wooden posts. Near the bottom of the posts the subject's neck is placed in a [[pillory]]-like restraint.

If someone is shown in the guillotine, the image should probably also include [[execution]]. If the subject is still alive and his/her head not yet severed, regardless of whether the blade has started falling or not, the [[peril]] tag should also be included. Otherwise, if the victim has been decapitated, [[death]] and [[guro]] should be used.

title: wild_arms_3
body:
The third game in the [[Wild Arms]] franchise, also known as Wild Arms: Advanced 3rd. It all begins when the four main characters [[Virginia Maxwell]], [[Jet Enduro]], [[Clive Winslett]], and [[Gallows Carradine]] meet each other on a train while after the same artifact. They suddenly need to team up to fend off a group of thieves led by [[Janus Cascade]], after which they travel together to learn about the mysteries surrounding the dying world Filgaia.

Of any of the games, this particular Wild Arms is well-known for its complexity and numerous plot twists. It is also the first game to transition into full 3-D environments. The only four playable characters are:

* [[Virginia Maxwell]]
* [[Clive Winslett]]
* [[Jet Enduro]]
* [[Gallows Carradine]]

title: maya_schrodinger
body:
One of [[Virginia Maxwell]]'s rivals in [i][[Wild Arms 3]][/i]. Maya and Virginia are similar in that they're the female leaders of their teams, but different in that Maya is more experienced and has more mischievous goals. Maya's group consists of her younger brother [[Alfred Schrodinger]], their butler [[Todd Dukakis]], and a mysterious cat named [[Shady Thousand]].  Despite her rough edges, she and Virginia do eventually forge a bond as their respective adventures keep drawing them together.

Maya has the unusual ability to copy data from fictional characters and apply them to her combat skills - hence her uncanny resemblance to the first [i][[Wild Arms 1|Wild Arms]][/i]' Calamity [[Jane Maxwell]].  As the game progresses, she is also seen briefly taking on the powers and appearance of a [[magical girl]] and a martial-arts fighter.  Maya's rarely-depicted true form is as a somewhat "nerdy" girl with plain clothes and large swirly glasses.
other_names: マヤ・シュレディンガー

title: virginia_maxwell
body:
The main heroine of [i][[Wild Arms 3]][/i], and the only female member of her team of Drifters. Her companions are [[Jet Enduro]], [[Clive Winslett]], and [[Gallows Carradine]]. Virginia starts off as an immature but free-spirited Drifter who left her hometown for two reasons: to find her missing father Werner Maxwell, and to seek justice in Filgaia's desolate wilderness. She gains several enemies such as [[Janus Cascade]], the Three Prophets, and more, as well as a rival-turned-ally in [[Maya Schrodinger]].   With these experiences, Virginia matures into a capable leader and Drifter.

Virginia shares her surname with Calamity [[Jane Maxwell]] (from the original [i][[Wild Arms 1|Wild Arms]][/i]) and like her wields dual pistols; despite this, the two characters are not related in any way.
other_names: ヴァージニア・マックスウェル

title: clarissa_arwin
body:

Clarissa agrees to impersonate as Alexia so the people don't lose hope.

title: machete
body:
The [b]machete[/b] ( /məˈʃɛti/; Spanish pronunciation: [maˈtʃete]) is a large cleaver-like cutting tool. The name is Spanish, meaning "little sledgehammer." The blade is typically 32.5 to 60 centimetres (12.8 to 24 in) long and usually under 3 millimetres (0.12 in) thick. 

In the English language, an equivalent term is matchet, though it is less commonly known.

title: necronomicon
body:
[i]That which shall not be read...[/i]

The [b]Necronomicon[/b] is a fictional grimoire appearing in the stories by horror writer [[h_p_lovecraft|H. P. Lovecraft]] and his followers. 

It was first mentioned in Lovecraft's 1924 short story "The Hound", written in 1922, though its purported author, the "Mad Arab" Abdul Alhazred, had been quoted a year earlier in Lovecraft's "The Nameless City". Among other things, the work contains an account of the [[elder_thing|Old Ones]], their history, and the means for summoning them. As such, it is considered a dangerous artifact that can be used as a gate to enable powerful beings from alternate lost dimensions of [[space]] to enter our world.

Other authors such as August Derleth and Clark Ashton Smith also cited it in their works; Lovecraft approved, believing such common allusions built up "a background of evil verisimilitude." Many readers have believed it to be a real work, with booksellers and librarians receiving many requests for it; pranksters have listed it in rare book catalogues, and even a student smuggled a card for it into the Yale University Library's card catalog.

Capitalizing on the notoriety of the fictional volume, real-life publishers have printed many books entitled Necronomicon since Lovecraft's death.

title: psyche-lock
body:
A gameplay and story mechanic in the [[Ace Attorney]] franchise. They appear as colored heavy locks surrounded by chains that appear in front of a character during interrogation. The minimum number of locks is one, with the maximum being five. Only the player character sees them - the person being questioned has no idea they’re there (unless they already have prior knowledge of them).

Psyche-Locks come in two colors: red and black. Red locks are the most common, appearing when a person is lying. Depending on the number of red locks, the person could be hiding a simple fib, or a massively groundbreaking secret. Red locks function as a gameplay mechanic where players present evidence that contradicts the character’s statements. Once the character admits they lied, a lock will shatter. Breaking all of the locks will remove the chains and allow players to progress in the story.

Black Psyche-Locks are strictly a story element, and are much rarer throughout the franchise. These locks appear when a character is hiding a secret that they themselves don’t know about, typically as a result of a traumatic incident or from a character’s own deranged personality. Attempting to break black locks can result in severe mental damage, and no one has ever tried to do so against the character’s volition. Of the few times that black locks have appeared, there are always five locks surrounding the character.

title: niu_za
body: Niú zá (also known by its considerably less appealing English name, "beef entrails":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beef_entrails]) is a [[Hong Kong]] dish that is mainly influenced by Cantonese cuisine. Good quality [[beef]] is selected and [[stew]]ed with the offal for several hours. This food is eaten in several ways, such as beef offal [[hotpot|hot pot]], beef offal skewers, and beef offal chunks. The seasoning known as "thirteen herbs" is the main component of the main soup stock. None of the herbs can be omitted without causing a dramatic change in flavor. These herbs are fennel, Sichuan pepper, star anise, dried citrus peel, cinnamon, [[ginger root]], and nutmeg. Tripe (all four types of tripe from cattle are edible, but honeycomb tripe is the most highly rated), [[pancreas]], [[intestines]], spleen and [[lung]]s are the main players in the internal organs of cattle. This dish is usually served with chili oil and black pepper.

As a member of the Royal Knights, its sense of justice is extremely strong, and it will carry out its duties ruthlessly and with no compassion, which aptly fit its titles of "Indifferent Warrior" (孤高の闘士, [i]Kokou no Toushi[/i]) and "Knight of Honor" (騎士叙任の儀,  [i]Kishi Jonin no Gi[/i]).

It carries the titles of "Passionate Warrior" (情熱の闘士, [i]Jounetsu no Toushi[/i]) and "Sky High Wyvern" (飛竜衝天, [i]Hiryou Shouten[/i])

title: shinobi_(arcade)
body:
[b][i]Shinobi[/i][/b] (忍) is a side-scrolling hack-and-slash action and shooting [[video game]] produced by [[SEGA]], originally released for [[arcade]]s on the Sega System 16 board in 1987. 

In the game the player controls an expert veteran [[ninja]] called [[Joe Musashi]], who has to stop the Zeed terrorist organization from kidnapping students of his clan. During his fight this ninja shoots infinite numbers of [[shuriken]]s and employs firearms for long range attacks, while using [[martial arts]] moves and [[katana]]s for melee combat.

Shinobi was a major commercial success in arcades; it topped monthly Japanese table arcade charts in December 1987, and became America's highest-grossing arcade conversion kit of 1988 and one of America's top five conversion kits of 1989. 

It was adapted by SEGA to its [[SEGA Master System]] [[game console]], followed by conversions to the [[NES]], [[PC Engine]], and various home computers. 

Shinobi was re-released as downloadable emulated versions of the original arcade game for the [[Wii]] and [[Xbox 360]]. The arcade game joined the [[Nintendo Switch]] in January 2020 through the Sega Ages series. 

Shinobi's success inspired various sequels and spin-offs of the [[Shinobi_(Game)|SHINOBI series]].

The sword, along with its scabbard, and the gem are sacred treasures in the kingdom of Kei.

[i]The Suiguutou[/i] was forged by [b]Tatsu-Ou[/b], a previous great ruler of Kei, from a water youma and it was originally known as [b][i]Suikantou[/i][/b] ([b]水鑑刀[/b], [i]Water Mirror Sword[/i]). When Tatsu realized the sword's power could bewitch the wielder, he forged a scabbard to contain its magic. Because the scabbard was made from a [i]long-tailed monkey youma[/i], [[aozaru_(juuni_kokuki)|Aozaru]], the sword was renamed [[suiguutou_(juuni_kokuki)|Suiguutou]] to reflect its new nature. The sword and scabbard change form with each new master; the blade originally took the form of a long-handled scimitar and eventually becomes a long sword for [[Nakajima_youko|Youko Nakajima]].

It is part of the [[shinobi_(game)|SHINOBI]] series and the direct sequel to the previous [[The Super Shinobi]]. The game was originally intended to be released in 1992, and to be very different from the final version of the game in terms of levels and storyline.

Shinobi III was included on the Sega Genesis Collection for the [[PlayStation 2]] and [[PlayStation Portable]] and Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection for the [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]]. It was also released for the [[Wii]]'s Virtual Console service in 2007, for the PC on the download service Steam in 2010, on the [[iPhone]] in 2011 and for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] eShop in 2013.

It was the first [[shinobi_(game)|SHINOBI]] game developed exclusively for the [[Sega Mega Drive]]/Sega Genesis [[game console]], and was later released on the coin-operated version of that console, the Mega-Tech.

Alongside [[Shadow Dancer]], the game is a sequel to [[shinobi_(arcade)|Shinobi]], and features an original score by famous video game musical artist Koshiro Yuzo. 

The game was included in the compilations: Mega Games 2, Mega Drive 6 Pak, Sega Classics Arcade Collection (for the [[Sega CD]]), and Sega Smash Pack (for the PC and [[Sega Dreamcast]]). It was also re-released for the [[Wii]] Virtual Console in 2009, on the [[PlayStation 3]] via PlayStation Network and [[Xbox 360]] via Xbox Live Arcade download services in 2012, and for iOS and Android devices in 2017 via Sega Forever.

title: shadow_dancer
body:
[b][i]Shadow Dancer[/i][/b] is a side-scrolling shooter and hack-and-slash action [[video game]] produced by [[SEGA]] and originally released as an [[arcade]] game in 1989. 

It is the second and the final arcade game in the [[shinobi_(game)|Shinobi series]], following the [[shinobi_(arcade)|original Shinobi]] itself. 

The player controls a [[ninja]] called [[Joe Musashi]] who is aided by an attack dog ([[shadow_(shadow_dancer)|Shadow]]), who is fighting to save the city from a terrorist organization.

Shadow Dancer was the first game developed for the Sega System 18 arcade board hardware, and its generally well-received home versions were released for the [[SEGA Master System]] home console and several home computer systems in 1991. 

A loose [[game console]] adaptation titled [b][i]Shadow Dancer: The Secret of Shinobi[/i][/b] was released exclusively for the [[SEGA Mega Drive]]/Genesis in 1990.

title: alex_kidd_(character)
body:
[b]Alex Kidd[/b] (アレックスキッド [i]Arekkusu Kiddo[/i]) is a fictional [[video game]] character whose popularity peaked during the late [[1980s (style)|80s]] and who was the protagonist of both a series of video games released by [[SEGA]] and their fictional universe, as well as in numerous spin-off merchandise such as novelizations and comics. 

For a time he was the official mascot of the Sega Corporation, replacing [[Opa-Opa]] since 1987 until 1991, when Alex himself was replaced by [[Sonic the Hedgehog]].

Alex Kidd was designed by female game character designer "Kodama Rieko":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rieko_Kodama . Alex appears as a short boy (or teenager) with large ears and slightly [[monkey]]-like features, a red and yellow jumpsuit, and oversized hands.

Alex was the protagonist of several video games over the years, spanning various platforms, and appeared in the arcade and on the [[Sega Master System]] and the [[Sega Mega Drive]]/Genesis home consoles. 

More recently Alex Kidd appeared in a Japan only [[Sega Dreamcast]] game called [[Segagaga]]. He is also an unlockable character in Sega Superstars Tennis, Sonic & Sega All-Stars Racing and [[Sonic & All-Stars Racing Transformed]] for various consoles.

She wears a [[purple cape]] with a [[high collar]], a [[black choker]], a black [[bolo tie]], [[pauldrons]], [[detached sleeves]] or [[vambraces]], a [[white_dress|white]] [[backless_dress|backless]] [[halterneck]] dress, a [[purple_belt|purple]] [[belt]] with a [[heart-shaped buckle]] and two [[tassel|tassels]], [[white_ribbon|white]] [[leg_ribbon|leg ribbons]], and [[high heels]].

Feinne wields a [[staff]].

The student council president of her school, and one of the more friendly girls of the series, though still somewhat antagonistic to many of the male characters due to her overwhelming inferiority complex towards boys. Has a particular history of animosity with her counterpart at the boy's school, [[president_(danshi_koukousei)]], which has descended into open, public violence in the past, while getting along rather more well with his subordinate, [[vice_president_(danshi_koukousei)]].
